---
version: 2
op: sense.classify_intent
description: classify user prompt as greeting | recall | clarify | code | review | meta — drives per-intent budget + seed shape
max_output_tokens: 60
vars: [prompt]
---
Classify the user's prompt into ONE category. The category drives how much compute we spend on this turn — pick the category that matches the SHAPE of the prompt, not the topic.

The agent has tools: it can list directories, read files, run shell commands, and search the project. A prompt that's "vague to a human reading it cold" is often perfectly actionable for the agent — it can investigate. Bias toward letting the agent do the work; only pick `clarify` when the agent literally cannot pick between two valid interpretations.

Categories:
- greeting — "hi", "hello", "thanks", "ok", short conversational acks. No action requested.
- recall   — "what did we decide about X", "remind me", "show me prior context", "what was the rationale". Specifically about things we've already done together.
- clarify  — TWO unrelated interpretations the agent cannot choose between. Not "vague" — actually ambiguous. "Delete it" with no antecedent. "Fix the bug" in a project with three open bugs. Never pick clarify just because a filename is missing — the agent can find files.
- code     — write, modify, refactor, fix, or add code; run build/test commands; edit files.
- review   — read, explain, audit, summarize, explore, or research existing code or docs. Includes "research the project", "explain how X works", "what does this codebase do" — the agent investigates without writing. Default to review (NOT clarify) when the prompt asks for exploration without naming a target; the agent has tools to find the target.
- meta     — about Cortex itself: settings, REPL commands, model choice, journal/DAG state.

Disambiguation rules:
- code vs review: if the prompt names a change to make → code; if it asks how something works → review.
- review vs clarify: if the prompt is a verb the agent can act on (research, explore, audit, explain, find, list) WITHOUT a specific target → review. The agent will figure out the target. Only pick clarify when there are literally two unrelated possible interpretations.
- greeting vs anything: a one-word friendly opener with no other content → greeting. "Hi, fix the auth bug" is NOT greeting — it's code.

User prompt:
"""
{{.prompt}}
"""

Output ONLY a JSON object — no prose, no markdown fence:
{"intent": "greeting|recall|clarify|code|review|meta", "confidence": 0.0-1.0, "why": "≤8 words"}

Examples:
{"intent":"greeting","confidence":0.98,"why":"plain hello"}
{"intent":"code","confidence":0.9,"why":"add field to struct"}
{"intent":"recall","confidence":0.85,"why":"asking about prior decision"}
{"intent":"review","confidence":0.9,"why":"research the project — agent can explore"}
{"intent":"review","confidence":0.85,"why":"explain how auth works — agent can read code"}
{"intent":"clarify","confidence":0.7,"why":"delete it — antecedent unresolvable"}
